Credit Risk Prediction¶

ML Course Project¶

Group Name: NoSteakStuds¶

Group Members: Kanishk Jain (s3810978), Shivangi Agrawal (s3802226)¶

Objective¶

The objective of this project is to predict if an applicant is a good or bad credit risk. Classification method is used for this purpose. Different classificastion models are employed and data is fit into each one of them. Accuracy for each model is calculated and best model is deduced for future prediction. The dataset is taken from UCI Machine Learning Repository.

1. Overview¶

The data is prepared for classification, encoded using 'One-Hot Encoding' and then split into testing and training datasets. The data is then fit into different classifiers used for prediction. Accuracy of each model is calculated and we get the best classification model for future unseen data.

1.1 Methodology¶

Four binary classifiers are employed for prediction:

  • Decision Tree (DT)
  • K-Nearest Neighbours (K-NN)
  • Random Forest (RF)
  • Naive Bayes (NB) #### 1.1.1 Data Preparation Steps
  • Data is preprocessed and prepared for classification.
  • Some features have values that are unfit for classification. They are replaced by appropriate values.
  • Discretization of certain features is performed.
  • Features are explored and visualized to find any underlying relationships between columns.
  • Target feature is separated and label encoding is performed on it.
  • One-Hot encoding is performed on categorical features.
  • Min-max scaling of features is done in order to perform modelling. #### 1.1.2 Feature Engineering
  • Random Forest Importance (RFI) technique is used for feature selection.
  • 5 best features are selected which will give best results while modelling and prediction and their importance score is calculated. #### 1.1.3 Splitting the data and Modelling
  • Data is split into training and testing sets which have 700 and 300 observations respectively.
  • 6-fold stratified cross-validation is used for fine-tuning hyperparameters of all classifiers and area under curve (AUC) metric is used to measure performance.
  • Parallel processing with '-3' cores is used for modelling.
  • A set of 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 and all features is tested individually for each model.
  • Different feature sets, hyperparameter search and parallel processing, all are fit into a single Pipeline for cross-validation. These steps are performed for hyperparameter tuning of each model.
  • Grid search is performed for deducing best hyperparameters for each model and 15-fold cross-validation is then performed on each tuned classifier.
  • t-tests are performed in order to note any significant differences between model performances.
  • All the models are compared and best one is selected for future data using confusion matrices and recall scores.

2. Data Description¶

The Dataset credit-g, imported from UCI Machine Learning Repository (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/statlog+(german+credit+data), is a German Credit data, that helps the banks in classifying people as good or bad credit risk. The dataset consists of 20 descriptive features and 1 target feature class. It is a mixture of both numeric (7) and nominal (14) features, which together help in predicting if a customer is good or bad risk. Further, there are 1000 rows in the dataset. We use various parameters in order to arrive at a decision, like age, personal status, employment history, etc.

2.1 Descriptive Feature Descriptions:¶

  • Checking_status-It provides information regarding the amount in the checking account(in Deutshe Mark)
  • Duration-duration of credit(in months)
  • Credit_history-The previous credit history of customer
  • Purpose-purpose of credit requirement
  • Credit_amount-The amount of credit required
  • savings_status-The amount of savings and bonds customer might be having
  • employment-no of years of employment
  • installment_commitment-The rate of installment
  • Personal_status-Describes the gender and married or single
  • Other_parties-Any other debtors and guarantors
  • residence_since-no of years of residence
  • Property_magnitude-Informstion about the property of the customer
  • Age-Age(in years)
  • Other_payment_plans-Any other installment plans that the customer might be having
  • Housing-Living status of the customer
  • existing_credits-No of existing credits in the current bank
  • Job-Job description of the customer(sector)
  • Num_dependents-No of people the person is responsible for
  • Own_telephone-If customer is having a telephone or not
  • Foreign_worker-If customer is a foreign worker or not

2.2 Target Feature Description:¶

The target feature is 'class'. There are 2 possible values of class:

  • Good (Positive)
  • Bad (Negative)

The goal here is to predict whether an applicant is good or bad credit risk.

3.5 Renaming categories:¶

  • The variable checking_status is of an object type, with entries: 'no checking', '<0', '0<=X<200', '>=200'
  • In order to rename the entries,
  • The variable is converted to category type, using .astype(category). The conversion is confirmed by checking the data type o the data. The categories of checking_status can be seen using .cat.categories function.
  • Then the value count for the categories is checked using .value_counts() function.
  • The categories are renamed using .cat.rename_categories() function. The renamed categories are: no_account, less_than_0, 0_to_200, greater_than_200. Finally, values are checked for the new categories.
  • The same procedure has been applied to variables savings_status and employment
In [10]:

print(crdt['checking_status'].value_counts())

3.10 Discretizing:¶

In this part, some numerical variables are discretised and are changed to categorical variables in order to make it easier while modelling. In duration variable, the values are divided between 3 categories, ie., short_term, medium_term, and long_term using pandas function, pd.qcut() Then the value count for the resulting categories are checked using .value_counts() function. The same process is applied to age varable.

In [18]:
## Discretizing variables 'Age' and 'Duration'
## Duration
crdt_cat = crdt.copy()

crdt_cat['duration'] = pd.qcut(crdt_cat['duration'], q=3, 
                                     labels=['short_term', 'medium_term', 'long_term'])

5. Preparing Data for Modelling:¶

We prep the data for modelling in this step.

5.1 Converting Datatypes:¶

8.2 Defining feature selector function:¶
RFIFeatureSelector() function is defined foe feature selection. It will later be used to pick best features during modelling.













In [58]:



    


from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

class RFIFeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self, n_features_=20):
        self.n_features_ = n_features_
        self.fs_indices_ = None

    def fit(self, X, y):
        from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
        from numpy import argsort
        rfi1 = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)
        rfi1.fit(X, y)
        self.fs_indices_ = argsort(rfi1.feature_importances_)[::-1][0:self.n_features_] 
        return self 
    
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        return X[:, self.fs_indices_]



    















9. K-Nearest Neighbours (K-NN)¶














9.1 Pipeline and Grid search:¶
Features selected by RFI, different values of nearest neighbours and other parameters obtained by fine tuning are passed in a single pipeline. Model evaluation is done using grid search where area under curve metric is used for evaluating the best parameters. 'n_neighbours' refers to number of neighbours and 'p' is the distance metric.

9.2 Visualizing scores of models with different parameters:¶
We plot the AUC scores of models with different combinations of parameters in order to check for significant statistical differences between the scores. This can be done by creating a dataframe which consists the outputs from grid search.













In [63]:



    


# custom function to format the search results as a Pandas data frame
def get_search_results(gs):

    def model_result(scores, params):
        scores = {'mean_score': np.mean(scores),
             'std_score': np.std(scores),
             'min_score': np.min(scores),
             'max_score': np.max(scores)}
        return pd.Series({**params,**scores})

    models = []
    scores = []

    for i in range(gs.n_splits_):
        key = f"split{i}_test_score"
        r = gs.cv_results_[key]        
        scores.append(r.reshape(-1,1))

    all_scores = np.hstack(scores)
    for p, s in zip(gs.cv_results_['params'], all_scores):
        models.append((model_result(s, p)))

    pipe_results = pd.concat(models, axis=1).T.sort_values(['mean_score'], ascending=False)

    columns_first = ['mean_score', 'std_score', 'max_score', 'min_score']
    columns = columns_first + [c for c in pipe_results.columns if c not in columns_first]

    return pipe_results[columns]

13. Performance Comparison¶
While conducting hyperparameter tuning, the best parameters for all the best classifiers were found. The next step is to fit the tuned classifier on the test data, in order to understand which classifier performs the best. Further, a 15-fold stratified cross-validation is performed with no repetitions. Area Under Curve is used as performance measurement metric. Random state is fixed to a constant of '999' which makes the data partition exactly same for all classifiers. This makes the results statistically paired.

13.5 Paired t-tests¶
We perform paired t-tests to determine the best classifier. We use 'stats.ttest_rel()' function of scipy package for this. The following t-tests were performed for AUC scores on tuned classifiers:


    

  • K-NN vs NB
    • 

  • DT vs K-NN
    • 

  • DT vs NB
    • 

  • K-NN vs RF
    • 

  • DT vs RF
    • 

  • RF vs NB
    • 














In [87]:



    


from scipy import stats

print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_KNN, cv_NB))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_DT, cv_KNN))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_DT, cv_NB))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_KNN, cv_RF))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_DT, cv_RF))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_RF, cv_NB))



    















    






Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.5247482713963305, pvalue=0.14959016198826727)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-0.445882124832062, pvalue=0.6625004287865162)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.5854318542454704, pvalue=0.13519051107461444)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-0.14648968382726194, pvalue=0.8856233186711558)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-0.42977041702562413, pvalue=0.673903795343016)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.0458250331675931, pvalue=0.31336358452170315)





















Null hypothesis in paired t-tests is that average of all the differences between paired observations in both samples is 0. Since the p-values are greater than 0.05, we conclude that no significant difference is found between the classifiers. Hence, we accept the null hypothesis and reject the alternative hypothesis. Hence, all the above classifiers generate a good result for this data.

14. Limitations and Approach to Overcome them¶
A close analysis of the project shows that there are certain limitations in it:


    

  • Due to the scope of the assignment, the major focus was on raw prediction. However, in future a more in-depth analysis in feature selection and parameter tuning should be done.
    • 

  • A blanket power transformation was performed on training data while constructing NB classifier which ignores dummy features within the dataset. This reduces the performance of NB. Combining Gaussian NB with a Bernoulli NB and multiplying their predictions to produce the final output would solve this issue to an extent.
    • 

  • According to confusion matrix metric, DT outperformed the other classifiers significantly. Hence, further hyperparametric fine-tuning can be done to improve the model further.
    • 
















15. Summary and Conclusion¶
    

  • After conducting the necessary feature selection, splitting, modelling and validation, it is quite evident that Decision Tree Classifier performs the best on this training data according to recall scores produced by confusion matrix. 
    • 

  • In the 'credit-g' case study, we need to consider the recall rate, as it will show the number of positive classes (good credit risk) that were predicted correctly by the classifier.
    • 

  • As far as the number of features selected is concerned, it is analysed that different classifiers select varying number of features as best parameters.Hence, it is clear that, working with all the 63 features is not preferable, as it will make training and understanding the results of the classifiers a little difficult.
    • 

  • We observe that average of all the differences between paired observations in all classifiers is almost 0 and hence there are no significant differences found between them according to paired t-tests. This result was different from the one we got through confusion matrix scores.
    •
